<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Fortitude.jpg" class="image" title="Fortitudo, by Sandro Botticelli"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Fortitude.jpg/180px-Fortitude.jpg" width="180" height="344" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Fortitude.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Fortitudo, by <a href="/wiki/Sandro_Botticelli" title="Sandro Botticelli">Sandro Botticelli</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Courage</b>, also known as <b>bravery</b>, <b>will</b>, <b>intrepidity</b>, and <b>fortitude</b>, is the ability to confront <a href="/wiki/Fear" title="Fear">fear</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pain" title="Pain">pain</a>, <a href="/wiki/Risk" title="Risk">risk/danger</a>, <a href="/wiki/Uncertainty" title="Uncertainty">uncertainty</a>, or <a href="/wiki/Intimidation" title="Intimidation">intimidation</a>. <b>"Physical courage"</b> is courage in the face of physical pain, hardship, or threat of death, while <b>"moral courage"</b> is the ability to <a href="/wiki/Ethics" title="Ethics">act rightly</a> in the face of popular <a href="/wiki/Opposition" title="Opposition">opposition</a>, <a href="/wiki/Shame" title="Shame">shame</a>, <a href="/wiki/Scandal" title="Scandal">scandal</a>, or discouragement.</p>
